= lesson 17: questions

Questions usually come in two flavours:

+ #emph[yes / no questions]. These are questions that can be answered with yes
  or no, positively or negatively.
+ #emph[open-ended questions]. These are like filling the blanks: who did it?
  did what? to whom? where? why?

== Yes / no questions

=== Question

Remember how in the previous lesson, we've learned to negate a sentence by
finding the first word in the verb? We do something similar to make yes / no
questions. We #emph[double] the first word in the verb, and put an #strong[уұӨӮ
  ala] in between:

#list((
  word("уұӨ¶уұӨӮуұӨ¶", "moku ala moku", "does ... eat?"),
  sentence(
    "уұҘ‘уұӨ§уұӨ¶уұӨӮуұӨ¶уұӨүуұӨҘ",
    "pipi li moku ala moku e len?",
    "Does the moth eat the cloth?",
  ),
  word("уұҘ”уұӨӮуұҘ”", "pona ala pona", "is ... good?"),
  sentence(
    "уұӨ•уұӨ»уұӨ§уұҘ”уұӨӮуұҘ”уұҘ©уұҘһ",
    "kalama musi li pona ala pona tawa sina?",
    "Is the music good to you? (Do you like the music?)",
  ),
  word("уұҘ·уұӨӮуұҘ·", "wile ala wile", "does ... want to ...?"),
  sentence(
    "уұҘһуұҘ·уұӨӮуұҘ·уұӨўуұӨ¬уұҘҘ",
    "sina wile ala wile lape lon supa?",
    "Do you want to sleep in the bed?",
  ),
  word("уұӨ¬уұӨӮуұӨ¬", "lon ala lon", "is ... at ...?"),
  sentence(
    "уұҘҶуұӨ§уұӨ¬уұӨӮуұӨ¬уұӨ°уұҰҗуұӨ¶уұӨүуұҘҙуұӨҚуұӨ—уұӨӮуұҰ‘",
    "ona li lon ala lon ma Mewika?",
    "Are they in the US?",
  ),
))

It's a little unusual to an English speaker! But you can see something similar
in #link(
  "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A-not-A_question=A-not-AB_form_4",
)[Mandarin].

=== Answer

English has a special word for 'yes'. Toki Pona instead does what Finnish,
Mandarin, Latin, and many other languages do: you reply with the verb for 'yes',
and a verb + #strong[уұӨӮ ala] for 'no'.

#list((
  sentence("уұҘ уұӨ§уұӨ»уұӨӮуұӨ»", "sitelen li musi ala musi?", "Is the video fun?"),
  word("уұӨ»", "musi.", "fun. (= It is.)"),
  word("уұӨ»уұӨӮ", "musi ala.", "not fun. (= It's not.)"),
))

The #strong[V ala V] pattern is very common! But there's another one:

#list((
  word("уұҘҷ", "seme", "what? which?"),
  word("уұӨҮ", "anu", "or"),
  word("уұӨҮуұҘҷ", "anu seme", "... right? isn't it? or what?"),
))

You can add #strong[уұӨҮуұҘҷ anu seme] at the end of any statement to make it a
question:

#list((
  sentence("уұҘ уұӨ§уұӨ»уұӨҮуұҘҷ", "sitelen li musi anu seme?", "The video is fun, right?"),
))

You can answer it with #strong[уұӨ» musi] or #strong[уұӨ»уұӨӮ musi ala], just like a
normal yes / no question! But the vibe is slightly different. If you use
#strong[уұӨҮуұҘҷ anu seme], it's more likely that you expect the other person to agree
with you.

== Open-ended questions

So we just learned that #strong[уұҘҷ seme] means 'what?', and it's the most
important part of #emph[open-ended questions]! #strong[уұҘҷ seme] is like a blank
space in the sentence that you want the other person to fill in with their
information:

#list((
  sentence(
    "уұҘҙуұӨ§уұӨ¬уұҘҷ",
    "waso li lon seme?",
    "Where is the bird? (lit. 'The bird is at what?')",
  ),
  sentence("уұҘҙуұӨ§уұӨ¬уұҘӯ", "waso li lon tomo.", "The bird is at home."),
  sentence(
    "уұҘўуұӨ§уұҘұуұӨүуұӨ‘уұҘҷ",
    "soweli li utala e jan seme?",
    "Who did the animal attack? (lit. 'The animal attacked which person?')",
  ),
  sentence(
    "уұҘўуұӨ§уұҘұуұӨүуұӨ‘уұҰҗуұӨүуұӨ¶уұӨӮуұҰ‘",
    "soweli li utala e jan Ema.",
    "The animal attacked Emma.",
  ),
))

The question and answer look exactly the same, except the answer appears in
place of #strong[уұҘҷ seme]. Everything else in the sentence stays in the same
order! This is unlike English, where question words (wh-words) move themselves
first in the sentence.

Protip: if you're ever not sure how to use #strong[уұҘҷ seme], imagine with a
possible reply first, and then replace the answer in that reply with #strong[уұҘҷ
  seme]. Convenient!

#list((
  sentence(
    "уұӨӣуұӨ§уұӨҳуұӨ–уұӨң",
    "kiwen li ken kama ko.",
    "Rock can turn into sand.",
  ),
  sentence(
    "уұӨӣуұӨ§уұӨҳуұӨ–уұҘҷ",
    "kiwen li ken kama seme?",
    "What can rock turn into?",
  ),
))

